C.  The response plan details the emergency response structure and includes personnel responsibilities and procedures within that structure.  In addition, the plan includes procedures for notification of local agencies in the event of an incident, facility evacuation, and decontamination.  Finally, the facility reviews emergency preparedness and planning, including plans for conducting emergency response team training and drills.

Riverside Energy management is committed to supporting the emergency response (ER) organization and its prescribed functions.  ER team members are drawn from the existing employee pool and the organizational concept fosters pride and emphasizes concerns for safe operation of the Riverside facility.  The well defined ER organization operates in conjunction with the local Fire Department and the Rock County LEPC to alleviate safety concerns about handling aqueous  ammonia.

Auditing Program
Riverside Energy has developed an auditing program for the Riverside facility's ammonia syste.  This audit program includes elements from the Program 3 requirements and has been established to provide a mechanism for periodic reviews of the various aspects of the RMP including:  
   - the physical ammonia system;
   - hazard review;
   - operation of the system;
   - maintenance procedures;
   - training procedures; and 
   - incident investigation procedures.

Although not specifically required by the RMP regulations for Program 2 facilities, audits are conducted every three years.  A copy of the auidt form used to conduct the audits is included in this document.

